title: YouTube Developers Live: Our Favorite Moments
description:
The entire YouTube Developer Relations team is in New York City this week! We'll each get a chance to share with you one particular show from our back catalog that we feel particularly proud of, or was particularly useful (or both).

We've collected all the videos in this playlist: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lzaYch2mqlU&list=PLhBgTdAWkxeChOSKPqPOfmoAGDMSs0GuC

title: Google Drive SDK: Cross-client authorization
description: Do you have a project with multiple components such as a server module and a mobile client? We'll briefly discuss about the new cross-client authorization capabilities of Google's OAuth 2.0 implementation and provide implementation details about improving your existing auth flow.

title: Google+ Developers Live: Python Quickstart
description: Join +Gus Class to learn about the Python quickstart for Google+. We'll show you how to run the sample from https://developers.google.com/+/quickstart/python and talk to a Python expert on how this integration best works for the language.

title: Google Cloud Platform - Greg DeMichillie (GDL-Israel)
description:
A talk from Google Cloud Event we had in Campus TLV.
More info: http://greenido.wordpress.com/2013/07/29/google-cloud-platform-app-engine-and-beyond/

title: GDL Italia - Creare un'app con AngularJS (parte 4)
description:
Ultimo episodio della serie GDL Italia sulla creazione di una prima webapp con AngularJS. Marco Moscaritolo aggiunge l'utilizzo di componenti esterni e spiega come utilizzare il comando orderBy di AngularJS.


Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist all'indirizzo http://goo.gl/MyQai

title: Google Wallet Integration with Instant Buy
description: During this session one of partners, Tagstand, will talk about their Google Wallet Instant Buy API integration experience. We will show a demo of the app followed by a detailed discussion on what it took them to build this app and integrate with Instant Buy API. Developers selling physical goods and services on Android should use this URL to get access to Instant Buy API - http://getinstantbuy.withgoogle.com

title: Custom InfoWindows in Google Maps SDK for iOS
description: Adding personality and style to your iOS application is an important differentiation from the competition. One way of achieving this is customising the InfoWindows that appear when a user taps on a Marker on a map. Display photos, price ranges, summaries, and ratings right in the map with your own theming and branding, empowering your users to achieve their goals quickly and effectively. In this Google Maps Shortcut, Brett Morgan will show you how to quickly customise InfoWindows on your Google Maps for iOS (http://goo.gl/8n3lV) integration.

title: App Engine at Google - Peter Magnusson Director of Engineering (GDL-Israel)
description:
A talk from Google Cloud Event we had in Campus TLV.
More info: http://greenido.wordpress.com/2013/07/29/google-cloud-platform-app-engine-and-beyond/

title: Analytics API, el poder de los n√∫meros
description: En este programa presentaremos una visi√≥n general de las novedades tecnol√≥gicas desde el equipo de relaciones para desarrolladores de la regi√≥n de sur de Latinoam√©rica. Seguiremos presentando nuestro enfoque de desarrollo, ingenier√≠a y las mejores pr√°cticas para implementar tecnolog√≠a Google favoreciendo la evoluci√≥n de soluciones tecnol√≥gicas. Luego presentaremos un escenario t√©cnico el "Enfoque Ninja" utilizando Analytics API y el escenario de implementaci√≥n propuesto. Y como siempre la participaci√≥n de la comunidad de desarrolladores con sorpresas y desaf√≠os.

title: YouTube Developers Live: Live Streaming with RadioLine
description: On this week's show, Ibrahim Ulukaya hosts Thomas Serval, CEO and Samuel Landau, CTO of RadioLine.  We will discuss how RadioLine uses the YouTube Live Streaming API to create a digital radio experience.

title: GDL Italia - Creare un'app con AngularJS (parte 3)
description:
Terza (e penultima) puntata della GDL Italia sul tema della creazione di web app usando AngularJS. In questo episodio Marco Moscaritolo predispone la struttura per effettuare il testing del codice JavaScript e ci fa vedere come AngularJS utilizza i filtri per visualizzare alcune informazioni.


Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist all'indirizzo http://goo.gl/MyQai

title: What is new in Chrome and Google Cloud? (GDL-Israel)
description:
A quick recap on the latest updates on: Chrome, Cloud and GDL episodes you don't want to miss.
For more details: http://greenido.wordpress.com/2013/07/31/chrome-google-cloud-quick-update-gdl-il/

title: Google Drive SDK: CORS support
description: Join us to learn more about the improved CORS support for the Drive API

title: Google Apps Unscripted - July 2013
description: Join us for our monthly Google Apps Unscripted GDL. During this session, we will cover the latest updates from the Apps Script team and leave plenty of time for Q&A.

title: Generating a refresh token for YouTube API calls using the OAuth playground
description: This tutorial demonstrates the steps it takes to generate a long-lived refresh token for your client ID/client secret pair using the OAuth 2.0 playground. This technique is useful for testing or for uncommon scenarios where you may need to generate a long-lived refresh token without having to include the 3-legged OAuth flow into your own applications.

title: Off the Charts: Google Analytics superProxy
description:
Publicly share reporting data and more with Google Analytics superProxy.
Google Analytics superProxy (http://goo.gl/Z5nc8c) is an open source project developed by the Google Analytics Developer Relations team. Click 'See more' to learn more.

Join Developer Advocate Pete Frisella to learn how to use this application to publicly share your Google Analytics reporting data and power your own custom dashboards and widgets. He'll also discuss how the Google Analytics superProxy removes the complexity of authentication, transforms API responses to different formats, manages your quota efficiently, and handles automatic updates.

Links: 
Google Analytics superProxy (GitHub): http://goo.gl/Z5nc8c
Google Analytics superProxy (developer site): http://goo.gl/IkCAJd
Google Charts (ChartWrapper): http://goo.gl/TqJfXT
APIs console: http://goo.gl/Ui0ULn
AppEngine: http://goo.gl/u6odjG

title: Big Query And App Script (GDL Israel)
description:
In this show of GDL-IL we talked about Big Query and how to work with it from Apps Script. As a bonus point, we show the browser tool of big query and the way to work with public datasets and specificly HttpArchive.
---
More: http://greenido.wordpress.com/2013/07/24/big-query-power-with-javascript/

title: Chrome App GDL: Inter-app Messaging in Chrome Apps and Extensions
description: No app or extension need be an island. Have your apps talk to each other using the Chrome API's messaging capability!

title: YouTube Developers Live: Google+ Identities
description:
On this week's show, Jeff Posnick chats with Sherry Listgarten, the product manger responsible for integration between Google+ and YouTube. We'll cover what developers need to know about working with YouTube channels that are associated with Google+ identities, including best practices for using OAuth 2 and uniquely identifying channels in your code.

Additional material:
http://apiblog.youtube.com/2013/06/google-page-identities-and-youtube-api.html
https://developers.google.com/youtube/v3/guides/working_with_channel_ids

title: GDL Italia - Creare un'app con AngularJS (parte 2)
description:
Seconda puntata della GDL Italia sul tema della creazione di web app usando AngularJS. Questa volta Marco Moscaritolo crea un primo controller, una prima view e visualizza alcuni dati letti da un file JSON locale, bindandoli in maniera dinamica alla pagina.


Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist all'indirizzo http://goo.gl/MyQai

title: Google+ Developers Live: Developer Policies
description: Join us for a quick walkthrough of some of our most important developer policies.

title: Google Drive SDK: Realtime API import / export
description: Join us to learn more about the Realtime API import / export feature of Drive. We will be joined by one of our Drive engineers from Boulder, Colorado to do a deep dive on this topic.

title: Maps Shortcuts: Google Street View in iOS apps
description: In version 1.4 of the Google Maps SDK for iOS (http://goo.gl/eD7jee), one of the most exciting features added was the ability to include Street View in your applications. In this Shortcut, Brett Morgan shows how to programmatically add Street View to your application.

title: UX Design for Developers, Episode 2
description: Join Nazmul and Izabel on the 2nd episode of the new GDL series "UX Design for Developers". This episode covers a few steps in the User Centric Design Process in detail (goals, personas, use cases, and features). Please leave comments in the G+ community at: http://bit.ly/uxcommunity. Visit the blog at: http://bit.ly/uxworkshopblog

title: root access Berlin #1: 6Wunderkinder on GO
description:
This first episode of root access Berlin was recorded in the new studio at the Factory in Berlin. 6Wunderkinder's CTO Chad Fowler unveils the backend architecture that powers Wunderlist and why they chose the GO language for the most critical part of their system.

Follow-up links:

Martin G√∂rner: http://plus.google.com/+MartinGorner

title: Build your mobile app with Google Cloud Platform
description:
Develop a mobile backend with Google Cloud Endpoints. Automatically generated strongly-typed client libraries for iOS, Android, and Javascript make calling backend APIs simple.

More info:
https://cloud.google.com/mobile

title: Chrome Office Hours: Performance
description: Join Paul Lewis and Paul Irish as they dive into some real world performance techniques that you can use to make your site screaming fast!

title: GDL Italia - Creare un'app con AngularJS (parte 1)
description:
Creazione di un'applicazione usando AngularJS, primo video in cui Marco Moscaritolo installa tutti i tool necessari alla configurazione dell'ambiente di sviluppo.

Il setup completo dell'ambiente di sviluppo si compone di:
* NodeJS: un webserver scritto in JavaScript, permette di eseguire codice JavaScript direttamente in locale, senza l'uso di un browser
* Bower: un package manager per gestire le dipendenze degli strumenti usati nell'app creata
* Grunt: task runner per eseguire delle operazioni grazie a degli script JavaScript
* Yeoman: tool per fare scaffolding di applicazioni, che utilizza Grunt per il processo di build e Bower per la gestione delle dipendenze
* Karma: test runner per eseguire test di un'applicazione
* PhantomJS: esegue i test senza la necessit√† di aprire un browser



Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist all'indirizzo http://goo.gl/MyQai

title: Monte Carlo Simulations with App Script and Compute Engine (GDL-IL)
description:
In this show of GDL-IL, we show how to use App Script and Google Sheets in order to build Monte Carlo Simulations. 
We will also touch on how to do it in the 'real world' by using Compute Engine and Node.js 
For more details and the code: http://wp.me/pB1lQ-12w

title: Maps Live: Google Maps SDK for iOS Version 1.4
description: The latest version of the Google Maps SDK for iOS, version 1.4, comes with great new features such as Street View, Indoor Maps, and a new look and feel. Mano Marks and Luke Mahe from the Google Maps Developer Relations Team demo these features for you and talk about how you can add them to your application.

title: Google Developers Tech Roundup
description:
Join Van Riper, Stephanie Liu and Adriana Cerundolo as they share this month's highlights in Google developer news, as well as their favorite hacker movie moments. Topics include Polymer, BigQuery, and Android Studio, and special guest Fred Sauer from the Developer Relations Cloud team brings viewers inside the Google Cloud Playground. 

Let us know what Google technology updates you'd like to see covered in future episodes by posting your request publically on Google+ with the hashtag #gdtech!

title: Google+ Developers Live: Google+ C#/.NET Quickstart
description: See how to setup and run the Google+ Quickstart in C#. We'll also talk briefly about how you can use Google APIs from a C#/.NET project.

title: Google Drive SDK: Push notifications
description: Join us to learn more about our latest launch - Push Notifications!

title: An introduction to Encrypted Media Extensions (EME)
description:
Slides featured are at http://goo.gl/Le9VQ.

Encrypted Media Extensions (EME) is a JavaScript API that enables web applications to interact with DRM systems, in order to allow playback of encrypted media.

In this Google Developers Live session, John Luther (EME Product Manager) and Sam Dutton (Chrome Developer Advocate) give an introduction to the APIs, and discuss the technical challenges involved.

title: Chrome Office Hours
Hello Polymer
description: Join the Polymer team for a Q&A on Google's new web component based framework.

title: GDG Silicon Valley: July Meetup
description:
Hans Dockter will talk about the new Gradle-based Build System for the Android SDK. This new build system has been developed as a Gradle plugin by the Google Android team. It is full of innovation, many of them demonstrating the unique underlying capabilities of Gradle. We will also introduce Gradle as such with a special focus on the new features that have been developed as part of the Android effort. For example more generic, platform independent dependency management and the concept of library variants for different runtimes. We will show how these new features are extremely useful for other platforms like Javascript, Scala, Java and C++.

This talk is interesting for both people interested in Android and people interested in Gradle who don't have a background in Android.

title: YouTube Developers Live: Enabling video uploads for your WordPress blog
description:
You can find the widget here: http://wordpress.org/plugins/youtube-upload-widget/

Join Ran.ge and YouTube this week to find out more about our open source upload widget for Wordpress. We will show you how it works and walk you through the source code for the widget itself.

title: Compute Engine in 5min (GDL-IL)
description: This week in GDL-IL we will see how to create a new virtual machine on Compute Engine. We will install a web server and work with it. Powerful stuff...

title: Google+ Developers Live: Best practices Ep. 3
description: In this Google+ Developers Live event, we will be sharing a few tricks for controlling the interactive post experience.

title: GDL Italia - Pubblicare ed editare un sito web con Google Drive
description:
Mauro Solcia spiega come creare un sito web interamente hostato su Google Drive e come usare Editey per editare i file HTML, CSS e JavaScript.

Alcuni link utili
* Google Drive - Publish Website Content: https://developers.google.com/drive/publish-site
* Google Drive SDK - Javascript QuickStart: https://developers.google.com/drive/quickstart-js
* Sorgente script Simple Drive Statistics: http://goo.gl/D8gAf


Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist all'indirizzo http://goo.gl/MyQai

title: Chrome DevTools, la evoluci√≥n de la Web
description: En este programa presentaremos una visi√≥n general de las novedades tecnol√≥gicas desde el equipo de relaciones para desarrolladores de la regi√≥n de sur de Latinoam√©rica. Seguiremos presentando nuestro enfoque de desarrollo, ingenier√≠a y las mejores pr√°cticas para implementar tecnolog√≠a Google favoreciendo la evoluci√≥n de soluciones tecnol√≥gicas. Luego presentaremos un escenario t√©cnico el "Enfoque Ninja" utilizando las Chrome WebTools para analizar la evoluci√≥n de la web para desarrolladores. Y como siempre la participaci√≥n de la comunidad de desarrolladores con sorpresas y desaf√≠os.

title: YouTube Developers Live: Instant Video Messaging with Invi
description: This week we will discuss how Invi uses the YouTube Android Player API to build compelling instant messaging experience. Feel free to ask us questions here: https://www.google.com/moderator/#15/e=202e4f&t=202e4f.6c

title: GDL Italia - Analisi di una applicazione in Dart
description:
Claudio d'Angelis ci mostra come realizzare una web application in Dart, nello specifico un client ed un server per il gioco del tris.

Argomenti trattati:
-Struttura di una web application
-Web Sockets
-Interazione client-server
-Server HTTP
-Manipolazione del DOM

Il codice d'esempio completo si trova su https://github.com/gdl-italia/dart_OXO

Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist http://goo.gl/MyQai

title: Startups tips (GDL-IL)
description: This week we talked about startups best practices and some tips.

title: Google+ Developers Live: Sign-in Best Practices Episode #2 - Dynamic Scopes
description:
In this Google+ Developers Live show, we will show you how to improve your sign in experience when authorizing your application to make API calls on behalf of the user.

Code from last week's GDL is here:
https://github.com/googleplus/google-plus-office-hours/tree/master/2013_06_26-sign-in-best-practices-ep1

The recently released PhotoHunt sample is here:
https://developers.google.com/+/photohunt/csharp

title: Google Drive SDK: Best practices
description: Join the Google Drive team to learn about tips and tricks on how to optimize your app

title: Maps Live: Visualizing Maps Engine Data on JavaScript Maps
description: Using Maps Engine layers, developers can visualize and interact with data hosted in Maps Engine on a Javascript map. These classes can compute the tiles augmented with Maps Engine data server-side or perform client-side rendering of the vector data, allowing the developer to dynamically restyle the vector layer in response to user interactions like hover and click. In this hangout, Josh Livni demonstrates this with a map of watershed data in Northern California from the Golden Gate National Parks Conservancy.

title: R 3.3 - Access or Create Columns in Data Frames, or Simplify a Data Frame using aggregate()
description: The with() function makes it easy to access many variables (columns) in a data frame for one-off calculations, the within() function can be used to create new columns that are merged with the original data frame, and aggregate() is useful for aggregating variables in a data frame across groupings based on one or more variables.

title: R 1.1 - Initial Setup and Navigation
description: Strategies that will make beginning R users more efficient: writing code using a "script" and navigating through directories within R.

title: R 1.2 - Calculations and Variables
description: Get acquainted with performing basic computations in R, creating R objects (sometimes called "variables"), and seeing and running earlier commands that were run in the console.

title: R 1.3 - Create and Work With Vectors
description: Learn how to create a vector in R using the c() function and the colon-notation (e.g. 1:5), find the length of a vector using the length() function, and subset vectors with bracket-notation and the head() and tail() functions.

title: R 1.4 - Character and Boolean Vectors
description: So far we've seen objects that use numbers, but R is also built to handle more types of objects. Here we explore vectors that contain strings or Boolean values (TRUE / FALSE).

title: R 1.5 - Vector Arithmetic
description: This video demystifies the different ways R performs vector arithmetic (e.g. addition and multiplication), covering topics including element-wise arithmetic, vector recycling, and how some functions are automatically applied across the elements in a vector. The seq() function is also introduced.

title: R 1.6 - Building and Subsetting Matrices
description: Learn how to create a matrix with dimensions of your choosing, how recycle a vector when creating a matrix, and how to query specific characteristics of the vector using functions such as dim(), head(), and tail(). Details and potential pitfalls for subsetting a matrix using the bracket-notation are also covered.

title: R 1.7 - Section 1 Review and Help Files
description: A quick review of the topics covered in the Section 1 videos: vectors, matrices, subsetting, and a few standard functions. Also learn how to access help files in R.

title: R 2.1 - Loading Data and Working With Data Frames
description: Get a refresher on navigating directories on your computer in R, and learn to load a CSV (comma-separated values) data set in the form of a "data frame" using the read.csv() function, which is a special type of data matrix. This video also introduces factor variables and explores the data in a data frame using the dim(), head(), length(), names(), and subset() functions.

title: R 2.2 - Loading Data, Object Summaries, and Dates
description: Learn how to load data in the form of a tab-delimited text file using the read.delim(), how to get a high-level overview of an R object using the str() and summary() functions, and get a crash-course into working with dates in R with an example highlighting why this skill is so useful.

title: R 2.3 - if() Statements, Logical Operators, and the which() Function
description: if-else statements are a key component to any programming language. This video introduces how to effectively use these statements in R and also clarifies some nuances of logical operators in R. Two related functions are also introduced: ifelse() as a shortcut that can be used to create faster and more readable code, and the which() function that retrieves the positions in a Boolean vector that are TRUE.

title: R 2.4 - for() Loops and Handling Missing Observations
description: This video discusses for() loops, which are a structure that can be used to execute a set of code repeatedly. Also covered in this video are the min(), max(), and append() functions, as well as how to identify and omit missing values.

title: R 2.5 - Lists
description: Learn how to create and use lists in R, which are dynamic, flexible R objects that can hold and organize other R objects.

title: R 3.1 - Managing the Workspace and Variable Casting
description: View all the objects in the workspace using ls(), remove objects using rm(), cast a variable as a different type using an as.[type]() function, and use lists or data frames to organize data or results.

title: R 3.2 - The apply() Family of Functions
description: When data are organized in a matrix or data frame, the apply() function can be used to calculate summaries (or apply a more complex function) across either the rows or columns of the data object. Or if summaries for each group (level) of one or more variables are desired, use the tapply() or by() function.

title: R 4.1 - Basic Structure of a Function
description: This video introduces the basic structure of a function, covering the declaration of the function, using an argument, and returning a result.

title: R 4.2 - Returning a List and Providing Default Arguments
description: Become more proficient in writing functions by learning the standard way to return more complex results from functions using a list, and learn how to specify a default value for an argument.

title: R 4.3 - Add a Warning or Stop the Function Execution
description: The most helpful functions return clear warnings and errors when something is wrong. This video introduces the warning() and stop() functions, which can be used within a function to report a warning to the user or stop the function's execution.

title: R 4.4 - Passing Additional Arguments Using an Ellipsis
description: Sometimes it is useful to be able to pass any extra arguments to another function. For example, if a new plotting function is created that makes use of the function called plot(), it would be useful to be able to be able to specify additional details to plot() automatically. This is possible using an ellipsis, "...".

title: R 4.5 - Make a Returned Result Invisible and Build Recursive Functions
description: Use the invisible() function in place of return() in a function to prevent the output from printing to the user's screen but still allow the result to be stored into an R object. Additionally, when building a recursive function, use the Recall() function.

title: R 4.6 - Custom Functions With apply()
description: In the last section of videos, the apply() function was introduced. A prebuilt function is often used in this function, but it is also common to write a new function within apply() or to apply a custom function.

title: Importing YouTube API Java samples into Eclipse IDE
description:
This tutorial demonstrates how to import the YouTube API Java sample code into Eclipse IDE. 

If you're using Eclipse Kepler (http://www.eclipse.org) or above, you do not need to install any additional plugins.

If you're using an older version of Eclipse, you will need the m2eclipse plugin: http://eclipse.org/m2e/

title: Running the YouTube API Java samples from the command line
description: This tutorial demonstrates how to download, build and run the YouTube API Java samples from the command line using Maven.

title: Google Top Geek E26 (in Spanish)
description:
In Spanish!

In this Google Top Geek we'll talk about YouTube and several of the YouTube APIs.

En esta ocasi√≥n hablaremos de YouTube y algunas de las APIs m√°s importantes: Player API, Data API, Analytics API, Live Streaming API y Android Player API. Para mayor informaci√≥n visita youtube.com/dev y otros programas en GDL.

title: Skia Path Ops : High Performance Set Operations for Geometry
description:
Ask and vote for questions at https://developers.google.com/events/794092483/
Join us for a technical deep dive with Chrome engineer Cary Clark about Skia Path Ops‚ÄîHigh Performance Set Operations for Geometry. Skia is the 2D graphics engine used by Chrome and the Android Framework. Skia's SkPath object describes contours containing lines and curves. Path Ops computes unary path operations like Simplify, and binary path operations like Intersect, Union, and Difference. Path Ops enable higher performance with OpenGL and a better mapping from Skia to Postscript.  Cary Clark discuss the challenges in creating a commercially viable algorithm and some of the arcane math involved.

title: Waterfall Antipatterns
description:
Slides: http://www.slideshare.net/jrvis/gdl-waterfall-anti-patterns
You've been asked to investigate why your web site is loading slowly. You've heard of WebPagetest.org so you enter the URL and run a test. What appears next is a colorful chart that looks like a Dr. Seuss illustration. Some bars are long, some are short. Some bars are blue, some are green. "That's nice," you say to yourself, wondering what to do next. It looks benign, innocently simple. But you know it holds many secrets.

The waterfall chart is a mysterious force to some developers. Performance gurus seem to be able to divine the ailments of a slow site at one quick glance. "But how?" you wonder. The reality is that anyone can read a waterfall chart - if they know that they're looking for.

In this presentation, YouTube web developer Rick Viscomi will help you to identify specific patterns in a waterfall chart, patterns which are the signs of a slow site. Using these newfound skills, you will become that performance guru and everyone will rejoice.Ôªø

title: Google Apps Unscripted - Google I/O 2013 Recap
description: Arun Nagarajan and Eric Koleda from the Google Developer Relations team give a recap of Apps Script at Google I/O 2013. They cover the launch of Scripts in Google Docs and Google Forms, the new Drive service, the updated HtmlService sandboxing mode, and the upgraded authorization experience. They show off the new guides and quickstarts in the documentation and then answer live questions from the audience.

title: Google Checkout Office Hours
description: Welcome to Google Developers Live Office Hours! We will be talking through the retirement announcement of Google Checkout. This time will be used to go through migration options, next steps on removing code and most importantly, to answer questions from the community. Please use the moderator to ask all questions.

title: GDC 2013 - Understanding Your Players Using Near Real-time Data Analytics
description: Michael Manoochehri from Google and Luca Martinetti from Staq talk at the 2013 Game Developers Conference about data analytics for game developers.  The volume of data generated by games can be immense and the insights invaluable. Learn how to analyse player behavior, virality, segment users, and understand retention in near real-time using //staq and Google BigQuery.

title: Compositing in Blink and WebKit
description:
Ask and vote for your questions at http://goo.gl/VjjIy

Blink and WebKit use a compositor to display web contents to the user's screen. But how do we take a render tree (the browser's internal representation of a web page) and display it using a compositor? How do we decide what content should have a separate compositing layer, and how does compositing benefit us?  In this presentation, Chrome software engineer Shawn Singh will introduce basic concepts of compositing, and then we will focus on how Blink bridges the gap between the render tree and the compositor. This is only a slice of the overall rendering architecture, but it will be fun and insightful for any web developers and browser developers with an interest in how Blink and WebKit render web pages.

title: YouTube Developers Live: Elgato Systems and the new YouTube Live Streaming API
description: This week Jarek Wilkiewicz will host Florian Dejako from Elgato Systems and discuss how Game Capture HD integrates the new YouTube Live Streaming API to make gaming fun on YouTube.

title: Google I/O 2013 - Level Up Your Android Game
description:
Daniel Galpin, Koh Kim 

Learn how to take your game to the next level on Google Play. Our annual game talk, with ways to power up your distribution, user acquisition, and retention. Earn the √¢¬Ä¬úGold Rush√¢¬Ä¬ù achievement. Score three stars in quality and be one of the featured games on Google Play.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: GDC 2013 - Create Amazingly Scalable Games on Google Cloud Platform
description:
Chris Elliott, a Solutions Architect on the Google Cloud Platform, talks at the 2013 Games Developer Conference about building amazingly scalable games. 

Quickly deliver compelling game experiences by leveraging the scalability of Google App Engine combined with the unlimited flexibility of virtual machines on Google Compute Engine. From 1 to 100,000 cores, learn how to unleash your next great game on the Google Cloud Platform.

Raphael Simon, Sr. Systems Architect at RightScale also joins Chris to talk about how RightScale integrates with Google Compute Engine.

title: GDC 2013 - How EA Builds Mobile Game Servers on Google App Engine
description:
Yanick Belanger, Server Architecture Lead at Electronic Arts, talks at the 2013 Games Developers Conference about how they build their mobile applications using Google App Engine and the Google Cloud Platform.  

Yanick presents an overview of how the Google App Engine platform propels the production of back-end servers required for connected, social games on mobile, with real-world applications of the platform's services and built-in automatic scaling.  He talks about how they architect their games and provides tips and tricks for developers.

title: Google I/O 2013 - Using Drive as the Storage Solution on Android
description:
Ali Afshar 

How you can use save files on Android and let the Drive SDK deal with the messy details of uploading it to the cloud, and having it available and synchronised on all devices.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google I/O 2013 - Ingress: Design Principles Behind Google's Massively Multiplayer Geo Game
description:
Brandon Badger 

Ingress is a massively multiplayer geo game that was recently launched by Google's Niantic Labs.  Players move through the real world using an Android device and the Ingress app to discover and tap sources of a mysterious energy. Players acquire objects to aid in their quest, deploy tech to capture territory, and ally with other field agents to advance the cause of the Enlightened or the Resistance in an epic struggle for the fate of humanity. 

Brandon Badger, is the Product Manager for Ingress. He's been a Product Manager on Google Maps, Google Books, YouTube, and Niantic Labs. He'll be talking about Google's latest efforts to create ""adventures on foot"" using Android and Google's Geo data. The discussion will focus on the the game design principles and techniques used to create Ingress, as well as opportunities to use emerging technologies to create new types of mobile gaming experiences.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google I/O 2013 - The Other Mobile Mapping Platform: Getting Your Maps into iOS
description:
Developers can learn more about the Google Maps API at http://goo.gl/58Hk5
Presenters: Luke Mahe, Mano Marks 

In December, Google launched the Google Maps SDK for iOS. With vector maps that allow a much wider range of motion and access to Google Map data and imagery, the SDK provides a powerful way for you to build iOS apps on your platform. This session will explore different ways for you to integrate your data with a Google Maps experience.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

description:
Martin Gannholm, Navneet Joneja, Sebastian Stadil 

Google Compute Engine's had a very busy year! We've made improvements to the underlying architecture to provide even better performance, released new versions of our APIs that improve the developer experience, and introduced many new features and instance types. Come join us as we guide you through what's new and cool with Google Compute Engine, and how recent improvements can help you build more efficient, scalable and cost-effective applications in the cloud.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

description:
Greg Demichillie, Urs H√∂lzle 

Senior Vice President Urs H√∂lzle will share Google'¬Ä¬ôs vision for the next generation of cloud computing.  He'll discuss how investments in infrastructure, software and people will help usher in this new era for Google and developers around the world via the Google Cloud Platform.  This session will also include announcements and demo important new features of the Platform.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

description:
Dave Santoro, Steve Martin, Todd Kerpelman

title: The Modern Workflow for Developing the Mobile Web - Google I/O 2013
description:
Matt Gaunt 

Building for today's mobile web, getting 60fps across all target devices, while still delivering a fantastic user experience is a huge challenge. We'll dive into all the tools for development, testing, and performance evaluation of mobile webapps. Understand how best to develop with immediate feedback from the mobile devices you're targetting, scale up complexity to avoid hard performance decisions later. We'll also review all the possibilities of device testing locally and in the cloud.
In this session we'll debut improved remote debugging with Chrome for Android and the Chrome DevTools. You can now do local tunneling for improved local development.
You'll walk away from the session with a solid overview of the landscape of mobile web tooling and feel confident returning to your projects.


For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

description: The new Google Maps look and feel is now available for the JavaScript and Static Maps APIs.  In this Shortcuts episode, Josh Livni gives an overview of the visual refresh, and shows how to enable it in your own maps.

title: GDC 2013 - Connect Mobile Apps to the Cloud Without Breaking a Sweat
description: Dan Holevoet, an engineer at Google, talks at the 2013 Game Developers Conference about building backends for mobile applications using Google Cloud Endpoints.  Google Cloud Endpoints makes it easy to build OAuth 2-protected, RESTful APIs and instantly generate client libraries for Android, iOS, and JavaScript. See how you can use this feature to connect your Android, iOS, and mobile browser applications to powerful backends built on App Engine.

title: GDC 2013 - Introduction to the Google Cloud Platform
description:
Ryan Boyd introduces the Google Cloud Platform at the 2013 Game Developers Conference.  Provides a high level overview of Google App Engine, Compute Engine, Cloud Storage and BigQuery.  These technologies allow you to launch an app without system administrators, while having the ultimate flexibility of root on a virtual machine. Get high performance asset hosting, and analyze terabyte-sized data to optimize games. 

Momchil Kyurkchiev and Andrew First from Leanplum then talk about how they made a platform to help mobile app developers do A/B testing to optimize their apps.  They step through various components of Leanplum and talk about their underlying design decisions.

description:

Google Maps and the Maps API enjoy huge popularity around the world. The Google Maps API is the most used API on the web. maps.google.com is the most used mapping site. In this session, the Product Management Director of Google Maps teams with the Product Manager for the Google Maps API and the lead Developer Advocate to walk you into the future of Google Maps.

title: Google I/O 2013 - Selling physical goods on Android with Google Wallet Instant Buy
description:
Jonathan Taylor, Michael Galpin, Prakash Hariramani 

One of the top barrier to mobile commerce is the ease of checkout. Whether you're selling office supplies, t-shirts, or fancy jewelry your users are faced with the same problem: providing credit card and shipping information via long complicated forms that are particularly painful to fill out on a mobile device. That's where the Google Wallet Android API comes in. Learn how you can use the API to make the shopping experience in your app simple and frictionless, and in turn drive up conversion and sales. 

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

description:
David Symonds

Come along to hear how to fully exploit the power of Go on App Engine and make your web applications the best they can be.

Come learn how Google+ Sign-In can create more engaging experiences in your app and drive more usage across devices.  This talk will introduce the technical concepts of integrating Google+ Sign-In and other Google+ features, and is a pre-requisite for other Google+ talks.

description:
Eric Bidelman 

http://moreawesomeweb.com

This session will cover the bleeding-edge features of HTML5 that you may have missed, focusing on features that make developers' lives easier and apps more powerful. A heavy focus will be on freshly landed CSS/JS/HTML primitives which address layout, performance, and specific use cases...especially on mobile: @viewport, @supports, intrinsic/viewport units, resolution & pointer media queries, User/Resource Timing APIs, JS i18n API, iframe goodies, and more.

description:
Developers can learn more about the Google Maps API at http://goo.gl/58Hk5
Presenters: Brett Morgan, Ken Hoetmer 

Location continues to play an increasingly important role in a variety of organizations, and the emergence of the cloud and mobile as reliable and scalable platforms has transformed how organizations use mapping technology to work more effectively, improve processes, and benefit customers. Learn about the different use cases that our enterprise products address and how organizations can easily integrate end-to-end mapping solutions to address a variety of needs.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google I/O 2013 - Device Agnostic Development
description:
Paul Lewis, Peter Beverloo 

We used to develop websites solely for desktop users. Today, we also develop for mobile devices, and who knows what new form factors will follow tomorrow. How are you expected to cope with many different constraints, and what are the right ways for approaching device agnostic development?

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Dart: HTML of the Future, Today! - Google I/O 2013
description:
Emily Fortuna, Sigmund Cherem 

Develop large apps in a structured language and still experience fast Edit/Reload development cycles? Indeed, the prophecy has come true. Get crazy productive with Dart's tools, smooth HTML libraries, cross-browser polyfills, and web components based framework. Come learn how you can easily and quickly develop web apps that work cross-browser on both desktop and mobile platforms. We'll show you how to build modern web apps with Web Components and dynamic data-driven views without having to wait for cumbersome compile cycles. Make a change, hit reload, and boom, it's ready for all modern browsers.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google I/O 2013 - WebP: Deploying Faster, Smaller, and More Beautiful Images
description:
Ilya Grigorik, Stephen Konig 

WebP is a new, open-source image format which provides lossy and lossless compression of images with significant byte savings: 30-80% smaller image files when compared to jpeg and png! In this session we will cover the latest features, news, and future roadmap of the WebP format. We will  dive into a few hands-on case studies and recount how large sites and applications deployed WebP, the challenges they faced in the process, and the benefits they saw and measured after the migration. In other words, a 0-60 primer on WebP: what it is, how to get started, the tooling, and the benefits - bring your propeller hat!

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Real-time communication with WebRTC: Google I/O 2013
description:
Justin Uberti, Sam Dutton

Presentation slides: http://io13webrtc.appspot.com

01:41 WebRTC across platforms
03:37 WebRTC APIs
04:32 MediaStream
09:44 RTCPeerConnection
12:28 RTCDataChannel
16:31 Signaling
18:43 STUN and TURN
22:18 Security
23:21 Architectures
25:03 Beyond browsers
27:15 Building a WebRTC app
29:56 Chris Wilson LIVE!
31:16 Links and resources

WebRTC implements open standards for realtime, plugin-free video, audio and data communication.  The core WebRTC APIs getUserMedia, RTCPeerConnection and DataChannel have now been implemented across Chrome and Firefox.

In this session, we show you how to get started with building a WebRTC app:
- what's a MediaStream (aka getUserMedia) and how can I use it?
- resolution constraints
- signalling: what is it and how can I set it up?
- servers: what do I need?
- RTCPeerConnection: WebRTC¬Ä¬ôs most powerful API
- RTCDataChannel: realtime communication of arbitrary data
- integrating WebRTC with Web Audio
- interoperability
- security

During the session, we talk through code examples, live demos and production apps.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live.

title: Google I/O 2013 - GWT Roadmap for the Future
description:
Bhaskar Janakiraman, Daniel Kurka, Ray Cromwell

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Mobile Performance from the Radio Up: Battery, Latency and Bandwidth Optimization - Google I/O 2013
description:
Ilya Grigorik - slides: bit.ly/11fZTNA

Building great, responsive mobile web applications means you have to be friends with the radio! title: Google I/O 2013 - Fireside chat with Research at Google
description:
Alfred Spector, Jeff Dean, Peter Norvig, Thad Starner 

Research at Google is unique, as it is conducted across the entire Engineering organization - by Research Scientists as well as Software Engineers.  Teams are integrated, boundaries are fluid, and we face challenges together while retaining a close feedback loop from our users. This enables us to quickly build, iterate, and launch new and innovative products that change the state of the art and thereby produce new research results. description:

Since then, MVP and the EventBus have become widespread in the GWT community and several frameworks have appeared to support them. However, there's still a lot of confusion over what MVP actually is and the best way to implement it. Many common solutions involve tedious amounts of boilerplate and overhead. In this talk, I will demonstrate that using MVP and the EventBus correctly is easier than you probably think it is and can be done without any frameworks or extra overhead. The end result is a more testable, maintainable GWT application that is a pleasure to work with.

title: Google I/O 2013 - Androids Do Daydream
description:
Daniel Sandler 

With Daydream, new in Android 4.2, an idle or docked device becomes an opportunity for your app to delight the user. But where did this feature come from? Should your app support Daydream? How easy is it to add a Daydream? How can you make yours more fun and engaging? Answers to these questions plus plenty of ideas and sample code will be provided for daydreamers attending this session.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google I/O 2013 - Standardizing Payments on the Web: Introducing requestAutocomplete()
description:
Dan Beam, Evan Stade 

Ever try buying something on the mobile web? Combine a mess of form fields and a soft keyboard and it's more frustrating than it needs to be. How many customers don't buy things from you because doing so is just too much work?  requestAutocomplete() is an aspiring web standard that will allow users to bypass pages of form fields with an imperative API for requesting details the browser knows. In this session we'll highlight how to enhance your site with requestAutocomplete(), how to quickly implement the feature, and what to consider when optimizing the UX of your ecommerce experience.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google Developers Live at I/O 2013 - Performance Alley
description:
Colt McAnlis, Ilya Grigorik, Louis Gray

Colt McAnlis and Ilya Grigorik of Google's Chrome team talk  to developers and Web authors about how performance matters in applications and websites, from framerates to buffering, load times and latency.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google Developers Live at I/O 2013 - Drive
description:
Nicolas Garnier, Louis Gray

Nicolas Garnier of the Google Drive team talks about the first year of Drive, its usage patterns, and its evolution.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google I/O 2013 - Making Location Meaningful with the Google Maps APIs
description:
Developers can learn more about the Google Maps API at http://goo.gl/58Hk5
Presenters: Kasia Derc-Fenske, Paul Saxman 

Location is a fundamental aspect of many location-based apps. But knowing where your user is located is only part of the story. Knowing where they're going and where they've been can fundamentally alter what you present to them. This session will explore using aspects of location to present a richer experience for users.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google Developers Live at I/O 2013 - Games
description:
Greg Hartrell, Duncan Curtis, Daniel Sieberg

Greg Hartrell and Duncan Curtis of the Play Games team discuss new services, demo Rip Tide 2, and talk about NFC features in games.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Automating Performance Best Practices with PageSpeed - Google I/O 2013
description:
Ilya Grigorik 

Come learn about the Google PageSpeed family: 
(a) Insights products to help identify performance problems (through browser extensions, online, and API). 
(b) Automagic optimization: open-source Apache and Nginx PageSpeed plugins that can optimize your site for you. See hands on examples, stats and case studies from partners (AOL, and few others).
(c) PageSpeed Service: explanation of the Google hosted web optimization product. See examples of advanced integrations with other Google products (e.g. App Engine, A/B testing with Google Analytics, etc). 
(d) Chrome data compression: an under the hood look at how Chrome leverages pagespeed to optimize pages on the fly and provides up to 50% bandwidth improvement for mobile browsers!

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google Developers Live at I/O 2013 - Cloud
description:
Greg DeMichillie, Daniel Sieberg, Louis Gray

Greg DeMichillie, Director of Product Management, talks about today's Cloud Platform announcements. Greg recaps what was announced and discusses why we chose to launch these particular products.

For all I/O 2013 sessions, go to https://developers.google.com/live

title: Google+ mobile recommendations
description: Watch how Google+ content recommendations work for your mobile website. Google+ content recommendations make it simple for you to keep users engaged on your mobile site by suggesting the right content from your site at the right time. Improve every visitor's experience by giving them more of the content they came for. Learn more at: developers.google.com/+/features/recommednations

title: Root Access: How can your startup make use of Campus London?
description:
Don Dodge interviews Eze Vidra, head of Campus London. Learn what Campus London is, what happens there, and how you as a startup can make use of it. Eze also announces Campus Capital Office Hours, a series of events that puts startups in front of investors.

For more Root Access, see our playlist: http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLOU2XLYxmsILjw2c4ImxWXvi4vPrLCjYv

title: App Engine for Startups
description: For participants in the App Engine for Startups program, this is an exclusive Google Developers Live episode with App Engine Developer Advocates Fred Sauer and Mandy Waite. They'll be on live to give an introduction to App Engine, share tips and, most importantly, answer your questions. Submit your questions using Google Moderator below, and they'll answer them live on air.

title: Dart - JS Interop
description: Using Dart and JavaScript together in your web app.

title: Maps Live: Skydiving at I/O with the Google Maps APIs and Chrome
description: Join the Instrument and Google Maps Developer Relations teams to get an early demo of "Map Diving" at Google I/O. Instrument's developers will walk through how they built the installation using multiple instances of Chrome mashed up with the Google Maps Javascript API v3, Web GL, 3D CSS, web sockets and node.js.

title: Automating Your Front-End Workflow With Yeoman 1.0
description:
Writing a modern web app these days can sometimes feel like a tedious process; frameworks, boilerplates, abstractions, dependency management, build processes..the list of requirements for a front-end workflow appear to grow each year. 

What if however, you could automate a lot of this? 

This session introduces you to the Yeoman workflow, a combination of three tools working in harmony to keep you productive on the front-end. Whether you're using JavaScript or CoffeeScript, RequireJS or script tags, this workflow can help you spend less time on process and more time on what matters -  building great web apps.

We will walk-through how to use Yo - a scaffolding tool for creating apps, Bower - a package manager for client-side dependency management and Grunt - a popular task-based build tool.

title: YouTube Developers Live: Next Big Sound
description:
In this week's show, Jeff Posnick chats with Kris Schroder, from Next Big Sound. We cover the analytics services his company provides to record labels and bands, and Kris runs us through a live demo of the site.

We then go on to talk about Kris's experience using the YouTube Analytics API, including some techniques for making efficient requests and a few of the best practices that he's run into.

We also tease the fact that Kris is going to be on stage next week at Google I/O‚Äîbe sure to check back after #io13 when we post the video from his session!

title: GDL-Israel on ChromeOS for Developers
description: This week with hosted Nissim Betito and we spoke about ChromeOS and how to hack it for developers. We show some powerful tools that let you develop on Chromebook and (of course) show how to install other OS on ChromeOS hardware.

title: Google+ Developers Live: Community Showcase
description: +Chris Cartland will host Google Developer Experts +Gerwin Sturm and +Allen Firstenberg as they talk about projects they have been working on, Google+ Sign-In, and the fast approaching Google I/O.

title: Writing Custom Events for AdMob Mediation
description: While AdMob Mediation already supports a number of ad network partners, you may want to include support for a new ad network, or show your own custom view in place of an ad. We'll show you how to implement AdMob's custom event API, and demonstrate some interesting use cases for what you can do with your ad space.

title: OAuth 2.0 & Google
description: Getting to grips with OAuth2 at Google.

title: Getting Started with Google APIs (Python)
description: In this session, we build and deploy a simple App Engine application using Google APIs (eg. Google+ API) and OAuth2.  We also demonstrate use of APIs Explorer, Quickstart widget, client libraries and App Engine SDK tools that make application development easier.  This session demonstrated by Prashant Labhane is in Python and you can find the equivalent Java version at http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tVIIgcIqoPw by Sachin Kotwani.  You can find more references about Google Cloud development at developers.google.com and cloud.google.com.

title: YouTube Analytics API in ~10 minutes
description:
YouTube Developer Advocate Jeremy Walker discusses how to get up and running on the YouTube Analytics API in roughly 10 minutes. You can find out more about the YouTube Analytics API by visiting our documentation:
https://developers.google.com/youtube/analytics/

title: Getting Started with Google Wallet APIs
description: We will give you an overview of the various Google Wallet APIs that you can use to sell digital goods, physical goods on desktop and mobile. We will go through steps on how to get started on each of the API.

title: Batteries Included: The Dart Toolchain
description: Rip open the box and start playing immediately. This tutorial will show you why we say that the Dart project comes with "batteries included." The Dart SDK includes all the tools you need to write, test, build, preview, and deploy your application. Learn how to customize your toolchain to analyze code, debug and inspect breakpoints, install and share packages, minify and concatenate source files, compile to JavaScript, generate Source Maps, integrate with continuous integration services, and deploy your app. Join Andrei as he shows you how Dart's rich tool ecosystem helps you create a fast-paced and developer-friendly workflow.

title: Improving Your 2013 Productivity With The Chrome DevTools
description:
The DevTools have evolved over the past year to offer a number of features that can enrich your development workflow, helping you achieve more common tasks without the need to leave your browser. 

This session introduces you to some of these features, including Workspaces - a convenient way to create and edit new applications. 

We will also look at a better Sass editing workflow, where changes can be made directly to your source files without flipping back and forth with a compiler to generate your CSS.

title: Google Drive SDK: Google Drive at I/O
description:
Tune in to hear what's happening at I/O with Google Drive! There's a lot going on so get some tips from the team on how to make the most of the event (even if you don't have a ticket)!

description:
In the latest, v1.2 release of the Google Maps SDK for iOS, we changed the way developers work with overlays. In this episode of Shortcuts, Mano Marks shows what we changed, how to update your code and some interesting ways to handle the overlays that you add to your app.

Code from the show!
https://github.com/ManoMarks/demos/tree/master/markers-new

title: GDL Italia - The Android App Clinic - Tema Holo
description:
La GDL Italia diventa "The Android App Clinic Italia", e in questa puntata Mario Viviani ci racconta come implementare al meglio il tema Holo che caratterizza ormai l'aspetto di ogni applicazione Android ben fatta e rispondente alle guideline della piattaforma.

Attraverso le due applicazioni analizzate, Trackthisforme e 2night, Mario ci mostr√† come utilizzare correttamente gli UI pattern dell'ActionBar e del Side Navigation, come gestire un layout fluido in grado di adattarsi sia ad uno smartphone che ad un tablet e che non teme cambi di orientamento, come si possono inserire delle mappe usando le nuove Android Google Maps API v2 e l'integrazione con Google+.

description:
Slides: goo.gl/XwwpL
GDL-IL on AngularJS with Shai Reznik. We talked about why AngularJS is a powerful framework and how you can leverage it in your next project. Some of the parts we covered: Test driven development, Dependency Injection, Dynamic HTML, the $scope etc'. We will have in the near future another episodes to 'dive deep' on specific topics. Please feel free to join us every WED at 14:00 Israel time on developers.google.com/live

title: Google+ Developers Live: Google+ Platform Insights
description:
Join +Joanna Smith and +Silvano Luciani for an introduction to the new analytics options that come with Google+ Sign-In: Google+ Platform Insights.  From how to enable Insights to what you can discover from them, you are bound to learn something new.  Leave your questions here to have them answered on the episode!

Learn more at https://developers.google.com/+/features/analytics.

title: Google Drive SDK: New Undo feature for the Realtime API
description: We recently introduced a new feature to undo and redo changes in collaborative files with the Realtime API. This useful new feature handles all of the complexity of undoing changes when collaborators are involved and can be implemented with just a few lines of code. This undo feature can undo any local change, so it is useful for all types of files (not just text documents!). Tune in to for a demo and to see just how you can implement it in your apps.

title: Maps Shortcuts: Directions and the Google Maps iOS SDK
description:
Showing people where things are is a fundamental aspect of putting a map in your app. Using the Google Maps Directions web service, you can do even better: you can show them how to get there. In this episode of Shortcuts, Mano Marks shows you the basics of loading and displaying information from the Directions web service in your app.

Sample code:
https://github.com/ManoMarks/demos/tree/master/DirectionsAPIAsync

Bienvenidos a Google Top Geek, esta semana vamos a platicar en la secci√≥n de noticias de campa√±as avanzadas de AdWords con informaci√≥n social de Google+, un par de mejores a Google Drive que cumpli√≥ un a√±o y mencionaremos el reporte de transparencia de Google.
Continuamos con los m√°s buscado y lo m√°s visto en YouTube y terminamos con dos noticias para desarrolladores: una con una serie de videos del lenguaje Dart y de una herramienta para mejorar tus aplicaciones para tablets en Android.

title: GDL Italia - Offline HTML5 Agenda (parte 3)
description:
In questa nuova puntata della GDL Italia, Sandro Paganotti aggiunge un nuovo tassello alla creazione di un'agenda in HTML5 capace di collegarsi al nostro Google Calendar e funzionare anche offline.

Questi i principali argomenti trattati nel video

Part of our weekly show for Google Israeli developers, partners, cool startups and HTML5!

This week we will dive into the world of 'web workers' and interesting cases like: http://greenido.wordpress.com/2012/05/20/web-workers-and-big-data-a-real-world-example/

title: Cloud Platform, Batalla de Persistencia en la cloud
description: En este programa presentaremos una visi√≥n general de las novedades tecnol√≥gicas desde el equipo de relaciones para desarrolladores de la regi√≥n de sur de Latinoam√©rica. Seguiremos presentando nuestro enfoque de desarrollo, ingenier√≠a y las mejores pr√°cticas para implementar tecnolog√≠a Google favoreciendo la evoluci√≥n de soluciones tecnol√≥gicas. Luego presentaremos un escenario t√©cnico el "Enfoque Ninja" utilizando las propuestas desde Cloud Platform y algunas de las opciones m√°s importantes de este conjunto de soluciones para presentar opciones a la batalla de persistencia actual en la nube. Finalmente estaremos conversando con la comunidad de desarrollo, resolviendo un desaf√≠o t√©cnico y premiando todo el talento regional.

*Claudia Ludlow, Angel Ventures*
As Project Director of Angel Ventures Mexico (AVM), Claudia will explain how VC works, the types of projects that firms are looking for, and more.

description: Join us for a chat with Dame Wendy Hall Professor of Computer Science at the University of Southampton, UK. We'll be talking to Dame Wendy about Computer Science in Education and how it is coping with how computing and technology now permeate our lives.

description: Free Range Games and Kamcord Discuss building your community with video sharing. We will demo Free Range Games' YouTube API integration in APO Snow (http://freerangegames.com/aposnow/)

description:
Chris DiBona, Director of Open Source at Google, is interviewed by Don Dodge about how your startup should use open source software. It's a given that you should use open source and perhaps contribute as well, but there are tricks to doing it correctly, so that you can scale, so you don't run into legal trouble and so that you can be acquired.

title: YouTube Developers Live: GDE Interview with Matias Molinas and Tim Wintle
description: Have you ever been stuck working on a problem only to receive a solution from a friendly person you've never met? Some of the most helpful responses on Stack Overflow and open source code examples have been contributed by our YouTube API community members. The Google Developer Expert (GDE) program is designed to recognize the active and passionate YouTube API developers who make these outstanding contributions. In this video, we interview YouTube API Google Developer Experts (GDEs): Matias Molinas and Tim Wintle. For more information about the GDE program check out: https://developers.google.com/experts/.

description: FanBridge powers audience development and retention for YouTube channels and networks. This week, we'll be chatting with FanBridge's founders and developers about how they're using the YouTube Analytics and Data APIs.

description:

title: Root access: How your startup should work with advisors, with David Weekly
description:
Don Dodge interviews David Weekly about how to use advisors for your startup effectively and what kind of contract to have with them. David Weekly founded PBWorks, a hosted wiki/collaboration service that serves four million people a month. He also started HackerDojo, a co-working space in Mountain View, CA, where Pinterest was born. David has been on both sides of the table multiple times: getting help from advisors for his startups and advising entrepreneurs on their startups.

title: GDG All Hands: Code Jam 2013
description:
Google Code Jam is back this year for their 10th anniversary! Mark your calendar - the Qualification Round will start on Friday, April 12, 2013.

Ten years after its inception, Code Jam continues to bring together professional and student programmers from all over the world to solve tough algorithmic puzzles. Last year over 35,000 coders competed, but it was Poland's Jakub Pachocki (meret) who earned the title of Code Jam Champion, and the $10,000 reward.

The competition consists of four online rounds, culminating in the world finals held at Google's office in London, United Kingdom this August. The winner of Code Jam 2013 will walk away with a $15,000 prize, the coveted title of Code Jam Champion, and automatic qualification in the Code Jam 2014 finals to defend his or her title.

Joining us today are Bartholomew Furrow and Igor Naverniouk from the Code Jam engineering team. Besides the fact that the Code Jam problems are fun to solve, it is also a great way to brush up on your programming skills for future job interviews. Please use the Google Moderator series below to post questions in advance about Code Jam.

WebP is a new image format which provides lossy and lossless compression of images, with significant byte savings: 30-80% smaller image files when compared to jpeg and png! Tune in to find out about the latest news, features, and the roadmap of WebP. We'll also talk cover some great case studies of WebP adoption, and take an in-depth look at how to author and deploy WebP in your own applications and web-sites!

title: Google Drive SDK: Building Drive apps entirely on the cloud with Google Apps Script
description: In this GDL episode, Arun Nagarajan from the Google Apps Script team will walk us through how to build a Drive SDK app with Google Apps Script. Arun will showcase several examples and the source code will be shared. Come learn how you can build Drive apps entirely on the cloud with JavaScript with Google Apps Script.

title: Shortcuts: Using Storyboards with the Google Maps SDK for iOS
description: Storyboards are a powerful tool for designing user interfaces and managing application flow in Xcode.  This Shortcut will go over how to use Storyboards to design user interfaces that include the Google Maps SDK for iOS.

title: GDL Presents Women Techmakers with Trisha Gee
description: Mandy Waite and Emma Jackson chat with Trisha Gee, a senior developer at 10Gen (the MongoDB company) about everything from the pervasiveness of technology, Computer Science in Education, what it means to be a developer, developing role models and Trisha's desire to make her way to Mars one day.

title: Root Access Talks Funding: Securing Seed Investment
description:
The startup world is new and exciting, but can also be hard. We're here to tell you that many others have gone before you and are willing to share their experiences, right here in our studio! Guest: Don Dodge.

For more Root Access, see our playlist: http://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLOU2XLYxmsILjw2c4ImxWXvi4vPrLCjYv

description: On this week's show, special guest John Luther, the Product Manager responsible for the WebM video container format and VP8 video codec, joins Jeff Posnick for a chat about all things WebM. You'll learn about how YouTube's using WebM (and how you could use it too) for both consumption and video creation, as well as hear about some exciting advances in video encoding that are in the pipeline.

Script It! with YouTube

In this Google Developers Live episode, join Arun Nagarajan and special guest Ikai Lan from the YouTube Developer Relations team to see how to use the YouTube Data and Analytics APIs with Google Apps Script. You will learn how write scripts to connect to various YouTube REST APIs and present information via Google Apps. Join us even if you do not have YouTube videos to learn how Google Apps Script can consume external services.

The sample code shown can be found here: https://github.com/entaq/GoogleAppsScript/tree/master/YouTube

title: Web Components Now with Dart - JFokus 2013
description:
From embeds to widgets to managing complex applications, you constantly face the need for better componentization as a web developer. Don't despair, help is on the way. The web platform is gaining a powerful new set of capabilities designed to better help you build robust, reusable, and packageable components. The component model for the Web, also known as Web Components is the new family of web platform features for declarative composition, to modern browsers today. We'll cover what they do, their status, and how you can start playing with these powerful emerging technologies today. In this talk, you'll learn how all the pieces fit together. Demos will be shown using Dart and how that helps to bring Web Components to modern browsers today.

Slides at http://sethladd.github.com/preso-dart-web-components/#1

title: Google Drive SDK: How to make your files Searchable
description:
During this event we'll take a look at how you can make your Google Drive files searchable. In more details we'll see why, when and how you need to set the indexable text on a Google Drive file. We'll also talk about some brand new features that will make it easy for you to make your files searchable.

Speaker: Nicolas Garnier

title: Google Maps Developers Live: The Google Maps SDK for iOS v1.1
description:
The latest version of the Google Maps SDK for iOS, version 1.1, is now available! In this episode of Google Maps Developers Live, Mano Marks and Paul Saxman demonstrate the key features of the SDK, and share where to go to start developing with it.

For more information about the SDK, please visit https://developers.google.com/maps/documentation/ios/.

title: App Engine: Cloud Endpoints, Pt II
description:
Following up last week's App Engine GDL event (https://developers.google.com/live/shows/76184973/), in this hangout we'll showcase the Cloud Endpoints Proto Datastore library (http://endpoints-proto-datastore.appspot.com/), which allows ProtoRPC message classes to be directly tied to the models used to persist objects. In addition, rather than interacting with ProtoRPC messages in our API methods, we'll show how to directly interact with the entities that live in the datastore.

Code sample available for download at:
https://code.google.com/p/endpoints-proto-datastore/downloads/detail?name=cloud_endpoints_tasks_sample.zip

title: YouTube Developers Live: BuzzFeed
description: On this show, Ikai Lan from the YouTube team will be talking to Sandeep Chayapathi and Mark Shuster from BuzzFeed about how they use the YouTube API in their mobile app.

title: DFP API Hangout with ADvendio
description: Join us as ADvendio shares how they help Publishers with their AdOps workflows by integrating with the DoubleClick for Publishers API. ADvendio utilizes the Salesforce.com platform to host their application and we know many of you are interested in some tips from them

title: GDL Women Techmakers with Yael Karov
description:
In this episode Dana Gabel and Michal Segalov (from Google Israel) are interviewing Yael Karov as part of Google Developers Live Women Techmakers series.
Women Techmakers reinforces Google's core experience that great innovation takes place through the collective effort of many programmers from diverse backgrounds, and great tech leaders come from everywhere. This initiative brings needed visibility to talented top women leaders at all levels globally --- we hope to raise the profile of technical women contributing to our industry. We hope this will inspire more women to join the tech community, utilize their creative technical expertise, express inspiring vision, and join other active women leaders in creating technologies on Google's and other platforms

For more on GDL Israel: http://plus.ly/greenido

title: Dart with GWT
description:
In this episode of Dartisans, I'm going to show you a variety of ways to use Dart with Google Web Toolkit. I know that there are a lot of GWT developers out there who would like to give Dart a shot, but they aren't sure how because they already have a large, successful app that's written in GWT. I'm going to show you ways to integrate Dart into your existing GWT application without having to rewrite it from scratch.

To do this, I've built a sample application that uses both GWT and Dart. I'll show you how to setup a development environment so that you can work with both technologies. Then, I'll show you a variety of ways in which you can get GWT and Dart to interoperate.

Download the source code and the transcript from bit.ly/dart_with_gwt.

description: This episode will show you how to get the most out of Google Drive with your web app by appearing inside the new Google Drive create menu, and allowing users to find your app directly within Google Drive. We will show you how to create a suitable Chrome Web Store manifest to make it easy for users to find your app.

title: Udacity HTML5 Game Programming (CS255) Course Launch
description:
We just launched our Udacity HTML5 Game Programming (CS255) Course and we're excited to talk to you about this on Google Developers Live! Join Colt, Sean, and Peter and special guest Sebastian Thrun (Udacity CEO) for an overview of the course and a live Q&A session.
To sign up for the course, go to https://www.udacity.com/course/cs255

title: Identity Hoodoo Voodoo
description: A plunge into some of the deepest, darkest corners of the identity conundrum.  This week: Securing your mobile app, with Tim Bray and Naveen Agarwal.  Pre-submit questions at http://www.google.com/moderator/#16/e=207d33, or join us and pitch in live.

title: Apps Script Crash Course: ScriptDb
description:
In this episode Arun covers the basics of ScriptDb, a JavaScript object store that's built into Apps Script. He'll demonstrate how to store, retrieve, and query for records, as well cover best practices for organizing your data.

You can download the source code of Arun's ScriptDB visualizer application here: https://github.com/entaq/GoogleAppsScript/tree/master/ScriptDbVisualizer

title: GDL Italia - Offline HTML5 Agenda (parte 1)
description:
In questa nuova puntata della GDL Italia, Sandro Paganotti ci spiega come creare una webapp che mostra un'agenda degli appuntamenti presi dal nostro Google Calendar, editarli, cancellarli e in grado di funzionare anche offline.

Questi i principali argomenti trattati nel video
* Impostare lo scheletro della nostra app
* Aggiungere la logica per la gestione online e offline dei dati
* Utilizzare LocalStorage e le Offline Application API
* Utilizzare RequireJS

Il codice d'esempio completo si trova qui
* https://github.com/gdl-italia/offline-agenda-google-calendar


Tutti i video della Google Developers Live Italia sono raccolti in una playlist (http://goo.gl/MyQai), tra cui i precedenti episodi dell'offline HTML5 agenda.

title: App Engine: Cloud Endpoints
description:
Come watch as we go from zero lines of code to a simple Google Cloud Endpoints API targeting the Python runtime. We'll discuss writing your own ProtoRPC message classes, creating API methods, and wrap up by adding OAuth 2.0 authentication.

Code sample available for download at:
https://code.google.com/p/endpoints-proto-datastore/downloads/detail?name=cloud_endpoints_tasks_sample.zip

title: YouTube Developers Live: Soundslice
description:
Please join in on the conversation here: http://goo.gl/Q8MGf. 
Soundslice lets you sync tabs with video so you can see (and hear!) them in real time. Adrian Holovaty from Soundslice will talk about their product and YouTube API experience.

title: Google Drive App Review: Atooma
description: In the spotlight today is Atooma, an Android app that integrates with Drive (and many other services) to make your device smarter and automatically perform some tasks when needed: https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.atooma

title: State of the Script 2013
description: Arun Nagarajan and Product Manager Saurabh Gupta reflect on the past, present, and future of Apps Script.

title: Edge Conference - Panel 7: Testing and tooling
description:
Sites have become too complex to build by hand, and too complex to test without automation. What are the tools we now rely on for authoring and testing? Where are the gaps? Where do we need to focus attention to improve support?

Panelists: Paul Irish, David Blooman, Remy Sharp, Simon Stewart
Moderator: Ivan ≈Ωu≈æak

title: Edge Conference - Panel 6: Privileged access
description:
Slowly, websites have been peeking outside the browser sandbox, though we remain some way off an interoperable solution for the holy grail of a website-as-desktop-app without any runtime other than the browser. How do we get there more quickly, and in the meantime navigate problems like conflicting and confusing user permission prompts, testing and updating, and do we get the access we actually need?

Panelists: Brian Leroux, Diana Cheng, Paul Kinlan, Petro Soininen
Moderator: Chris Heilmann

title: Edge Conference - Panel 5: Input
description:
How do we write web apps that are agnostic to different input technologies? What about devices that combine touch and mouse, and what of new interaction methods like remote controls, speech and 3D gestures? What problems do we encounter when we expand support to encompass embedded browsers in devices like kiosks, TVs, games consoles, in-flight and in-car screens?

Panelists: Matt Caruana Galizia, Maired Buchan, Francois Doust, Boris Smus
Moderator: Pete LePage

title: Edge Conference - Panel 4: Responsive Layout
description:
Why are some designs easy to implement and others almost impossible? Can we make it easier to do magazine style column layout, fitted wrapping or embedding sandboxed content? For those aiming for truly responsive design, are variables like CPU power, viewing distance, input interface and pixel density just as important as viewport-width?

Panelists: George Crawford, Razvan Caliman, Andy Hume
Moderator: Amber Weinberg

title: Edge Conference - Panel 3: Performance
description:
How can we get faster repaints, more frames per second, quicker layout updates? Why are in-browser operations still perceptibly slower than native? And with page session time growing dramatically, are web developers worried enough about memory leaks and garbage collection?

Panelists: Shane O'Sullivan, Rowan Beenje, Pavel Feldman, Chris Lord
Moderator: Matt Delaney

title: Functions are Fun, pt 1 - Dart Tips, ep. 6
description:
(Part 6 in a series about Dart's language and libraries. Posted to GoogleDevelopers as a treat, for all videos, see http://dartlang.org/dart-tips/)

Functions are the basic building blocks for any app. Dart supports top-level functions, optional parameters, default parameter values, and more. Watch this episode to learn about the basics of functions in Dart.

Our thanks go out to Marakana for producing this series, which is available in it's entirety at   http://dartlang.org/dart-tips/

title: Edge Conference - Panel 2: Network
description:
It's easy to poke fun at websites with multi-megabyte pages, but latency and number of round trips are the biggest killers of page load performance, especially over 3G. How can we get the best out of the network and not let it slow down our apps? What's the best way to handle foreign resources, dependency management, batching and minification?

Panelists: Ilya Grigorik, John Cleveley, Andy Davies, Jackson Gabbard
Moderator: Steve Thair

title: Behind the div's: A Look at Find Your Way To Oz
